= El paro cívico

The coordinadoras call it: a National Civic Strike against the austerity — CNTE teachers, CONAMUP's colonias, the peasant currents, the independent unions, the whole insurgent society assembled in one instrument. Not a general strike; the CTM's grip makes that impossible. A civic one: streets, markets, schools, buses — the country of the unorganized, organizing for a day.

The Party's networks are wired through every convening organization. The question is whether to throw the entire apparatus behind a weapon nobody has tested.

- @todo: Everything in. If the civic strike works, the crisis decade has found its weapon.
- @medido: Support without betting the house — contingents, presses, lawyers, but the Party's name second.

@todo
choose-if: organizers >= 3 and funds >= 3
unavailable-subtitle: Un paro nacional se construye con cuadros y caja.
on-arrival: funds -= 3; huelgas += 10; sup_colonos += 4; sup_workers += 2; political_capital += 3; expediente += 3; represion += 2

The day is real: markets shuttered in twenty cities, the colonias silent, buses thin. Not the earthquake its convokers dreamed — the CTM's Mexico goes to work — but the largest coordinated protest since the Tendencia, and the government's economists notice that austerity now has an organized opposition with a working telephone tree. So does Bartlett.

@medido
on-arrival: huelgas += 4; sup_colonos += 1; unity += 1

The contingents march, the presses print, the Party's name stays in the second paragraph. Proportionate — and noted with a certain coolness by the coordinadora people, who keep accounts of enthusiasm the way bankers keep collateral. The instrument fires at half its charge; whose fault that was will be argued for years.
